=== Ch2_Age_Intro ===
Chapter 2: Restricting social media by age. # diagram: age_funnel.jpg

This is the core of the consultation—and where the framing matters most.

Four questions that form a funnel. Watch how they work.

*   [Show me.]
    -> Ch2_Q12

=== Ch2_Q12 ===
Question 12 asks:

"Would you support a legal requirement for social media services to have a minimum age of access?"

Yes / No / Don't know.

*   [Seems straightforward?]
    -> Ch2_Q12_Analysis

=== Ch2_Q12_Analysis ===
The question doesn't define "social media." Is YouTube social media? WhatsApp? Roblox? Discord? Minecraft with chat enabled?

The consultation document discusses this later—but the question itself doesn't. Many respondents will answer "yes" imagining TikTok and Instagram, not realising the scope could extend to platforms their children use safely.

A high "Yes" percentage gives a mandate that can be applied very broadly. The definition gets decided later, by government, without another consultation.

Also notice: any "Yes" here is a "Yes" to age verification for everyone. There's no way to enforce a minimum age without checking every user's age.

*   [What about gaming?]
    -> Ch2_Gaming_Note
*   [Next question — the age they're proposing.]
    -> Ch2_Q13

=== Ch2_Gaming_Note ===
Here's something the consultation buries: gaming platforms are discussed extensively in the consultation document's framing and analysis, but the questions themselves never mention gaming directly.

The document talks about Roblox, Fortnite, and online gaming alongside social media. If these restrictions apply to platforms with user-to-user interaction, that includes most online games.

A large portion of the public might react very differently if the question was: "Should your child need to verify their identity to play games online?"

But it isn't framed that way.

*   [Next question — the age they're proposing.]
    -> Ch2_Q13

=== Ch2_Q13 ===
Question 13 asks:

"To what extent do you agree or disagree: Social media services should have a minimum age of access of at least 16 and should not be accessible to any children under that age."

Strongly agree / Somewhat agree / Neither / Somewhat disagree / Strongly disagree / Don't know.

*   [What's the trick here?]
    -> Ch2_Q13_Analysis

=== Ch2_Q13_Analysis ===
The question presupposes that Q12 was "Yes." There's no option for "I don't support a minimum age at all"—you can only "strongly disagree," which gets reported as a minority position.

The scale is anchored at 16—the maximum being proposed. This is a well-known technique called "anchoring bias." Starting high makes lower numbers feel like a reasonable compromise.

If this gets majority support, the policy writes itself. If not, they have Q14 as a fallback.

*   [Show me Q14.]
    -> Ch2_Q14

=== Ch2_Q14 ===
Question 14 asks:

"Would you support a legal requirement for social media services to have a minimum age of access lower than 16? If so, at what age would you set it?"

Yes – 13 / Yes – 14 / Yes – 15 / No – not lower than 16 / Other / Don't know.

*   [I see where this is going.]
    -> Ch2_Q14_Analysis

=== Ch2_Q14_Analysis ===
This is the bottom of the funnel.

The framing is "lower than 16"—not "what age do you think is appropriate, if any?" Every single option delivers a ban. There is no "I don't support a minimum age" option. "Don't know" is the closest escape hatch.

Here's how this plays out in the consultation summary:

Q12: "X% supported a minimum age" (ignoring that many didn't understand the scope)
Q13: "Y% supported 16" (the anchor)
Q14: "Of those who didn't support 16, Z% supported 13-15" (the fallback)

Result: near-universal support for some form of ban. The only debate is the number. The principle of universal age verification is established as consensus.

They're going with age verification for everyone regardless of what age you pick. The consultation is designed so that's the only possible conclusion.

*   [What about Question 15?]
    -> Ch2_Q15
*   [This is manipulative. What can I do?]
    -> Ch2_Age_Response

=== Ch2_Q15 ===
Question 15 asks:

"What do you think the impacts would be of having a minimum age requirement higher than 13 for social media services?"

This is a free-text box—and it's where you have the most power.

*   [How should I approach this?]
    -> Ch2_Age_Response

=== Ch2_Age_Response ===
If you believe age restrictions are the wrong approach, Q15 is where you say so—clearly and in your own words.

Some things to think about (not template text—think about which of these matter to you personally):

The "cliff edge" problem: children turning 16 with zero digital literacy or resilience.

Australia's experience—early evidence suggests displacement to less safe platforms rather than reduced usage.

That enforcement requires age verification for ALL users, not just children. Your data too.

That on-device parental controls already exist, work without surveillance infrastructure, and let families make their own decisions.

If you support parental controls and education over bans, say it here. Say it clearly. And say it in as many free-text boxes as you can throughout the consultation.

